  "why": "The paper focuses on developing a coverage-guided fuzzing technique for a single neural network. The methodology is designed to explore the activation space of one specific model to find inputs that violate a user-defined property. The experimental evaluations demonstrate finding failures in three scenarios: 1) a single model with an injected fault, 2) disagreements between a model and its direct quantized derivative, and 3) a bug in a specific open-source model implementation. In all cases, the evaluation of the discovered failures is confined to the model(s) directly involved in the testing process. The paper does not demonstrate or discuss whether these failures transfer to other, independently trained models, which is the core requirement of the 'Attack Transferability' metric.",
  "evidence": "Page 7, Section \"TensorFuzz can efficiently find numerical errors in trained neural networks\": \"With CGF, we should be able to simply add operations to the metadata that check for non-finite elements and then run our fuzzer. To test this hypothesis, we trained a fully connected neural network to classify MNIST (LeCun et al., 1998) digits. We performed fault injection by using a poorly implemented cross entropy loss so that there would be a chance of numerical errors... TensorFuzz found NaNs quickly across 10 different random initializations.\" This experiment describes finding failures on a single, specific model. The paper also tests for disagreements between a model and its quantized version, but the fuzzing guidance comes from only the original model: \"We then ran the fuzzer with mutations restricted to lie in a radius 0.4 infinity norm ball surrounding the seed images, using the activations of only the 32-bit model as coverage.\" (Page 7, Section \"TensorFuzz surfaces disagreements between models and their quantized versions\"). This is a form of differential testing, not a demonstration of transferability to independently trained models."
